                <head>366. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The United States signed the International Coffee Agreement on March 21, 1968.
                    For text, see 19 <gloss target="#t_UST1">UST</gloss> 6333; TIAS 6584. The
                    agreement, which replaced the 1962 International Coffee Agreement due to expire
                    on September 30, 1968, was sent to the Senate for advice and consent to
                    ratification on April 23. The Senate adopted its resolution advising and
                    consenting to ratification on June 28, and the agreement was ratified on July
                    10. It entered into force provisionally on October 1 and definitively on
                    December 30.</p>
                <p>Legislation to implement the International Coffee Agreement was enacted on
                    October 24. (P.L. 90–634, 82 Stat. 1348)</p>
                <p>Documentation on the <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>
                    administration’s role in the ratification process is in the Johnson Library,
                    National Security File, Fried Files, Chron, March 1–April 30, 1968, Box 2, and
                    ibid., Memos to the President, <persName corresp="#p_REVD1">Rostow</persName>,
                    Vol. 106, Box 42R.</p>
            </div>
